(((((((((((((((((angela))))))))))))))  i'm glad the surgery went well, but
saddened by how much more damage there was than was anticipated.

boy, you must have been as confused hearing as i was reading what he said
about his being concerned with pain management and not knowing what to give
you "along with" (?) your other drugs.  what the heck could he possibly mean
by he "doesn't know"?   like, did he think you were going to take both,
oxycontin and the post-op pain med?  of course you wouldn't; you have more
sense than that.  and even if he thought you didn't, he could have
instructed you to stop the other meds and use just the post-op med, like my
surgeon automatically does.  he knows, there are other post-op pain meds he
could have prescribed that would help you, unless you have alergies to them,
like morphene or morphene derivatives or demerol.  i hope, by now, you've
already called to get better post-op pain management for yourself.

he sounds a teensy bit spacey to me.  i could be wrong, but it seems to me
that pain meds would mask the symptoms/how much the damage affects your
function, not the amount of damage itself.  the emg/nc study should have
given a reasonable indication of the amount of damage.

here's hoping your post-op recovery goes smoothly, angela, and that you heal
quickly.

kate

